                <fr:title text="Jordan algebra">Jordan algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a field. A <html:dfn>Jordan algebra</html:dfn> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is a nonassociative algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> whose multiplication satisfies:</html:p>
                <html:ol><html:li>commutative: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[xy=yx]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Jordan identity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(xy)(xx)=x(y(xx))]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
                <html:p>Note that Springer and Veldkamp's <fr:link href="/veldkamp-2000-octonions/" title="Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups" uri="http://localhost:8000/veldkamp-2000-octonions/" display-uri="veldkamp-2000-octonions" type="local">Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups</fr:link> (remark 5.1.7, pg 122) note that the character of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {char}(J)\neq  2]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/jordan-0002/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>jordan-0002</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/jordan-0002/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Hermitian matrices over a field forms a Jordan algebra">Hermitian matrices over a field forms a Jordan algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>example</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source">
                  <fr:link href="/hall-2024-sandwich/" title="Sandwich operators and Einstein deformations of compact symmetric spaces related to Jordan algebras" uri="http://localhost:8000/hall-2024-sandwich/" display-uri="hall-2024-sandwich" type="local">[hall-2024-sandwich]</fr:link>
                </fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {A}]]></fr:tex> be a (real) normed division algebra. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(n,\mathbb {A})]]></fr:tex> be the space of <fr:link href="/matrix-0008/" title="Hermitian matrix" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-0008/" display-uri="matrix-0008" type="local">Hermitian <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex></fr:link> matrices with entries in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {A}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}_{0}(n,\mathbb {A})]]></fr:tex> be the subspace of traceless matrices.</html:p><html:p>We define the <html:dfn>Jordan product</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(n,\mathbb {A})]]></fr:tex> to be:</html:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[A\circ  B = \frac {1}{2}(AB+BA)]]></fr:tex><html:p>When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {A}]]></fr:tex> is associative, this forms a Jordan algebra.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>21</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The claim is that this forms a Jordan algebra. We need to verify that Jordan product satisfies both axioms (commutativity and the Jordan identity).</html:p>

<html:p>We observe this product is commutative since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[AB+BA=BA+AB]]></fr:tex> (thanks to the commutativity of addition) and furthermore it is linear in the first slot (therefore bilinear, i.e., it distributes over addition).</html:p>

<html:p>Let us now verify the Jordan product satisfies the Jordan identity.</html:p>

<html:p>We see that:</html:p>

<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}
8(A\circ  B)\circ (A\circ  A) &= 2(AB+BA)\circ (A^{2}+A^{2})\\
&= 2(AB+BA)A^{2} + 4A^{2}(AB+BA)\\
&= 2ABA^{2}+2BA^{3}+2A^{3}B+2A^{2}B
\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>

<html:p>and</html:p>

<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}
8A\circ (B\circ (A\circ  A)) &= 4A\circ (BA^{2}+A^{2}B)\\
&= 2A(BA^{2}+A^{2}B)+2(BA^{2}+A^{2}B)A\\
&= 2ABA^{2} + 2A^{3}B + 2BA^{3} + 2A^{2}B
\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>

<html:p>We see that these two are equal to each other, therefore satisfies the Jordan identity. Hence it is a Jordan algebra.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
